\n!Opposition<br />Score\n!Opposition<br />Score\n!Rank\n!Opposition<br />Score\n!Opposition<br />Score\n!Opposition<br />Score\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|[[Ivory Coast national under-23 football team|Ivory Coast men's]]\n|align=left|[[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Men's tournament]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n===Men's tournament===\n{{main article|Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's qualification}}\n[[Ivory Coast national under-23 football team|Ivory Coast men's football team]] qualified for the Games by advancing to the final match of the [[2019 Africa U-23 Cup of Nations]], signifying the country's recurrence to the Olympic tournament after a twelve-year absence.<ref>{{cite news|title=C\u00f4te d'Ivoire and Egypt earn Tokyo 2020 berths|url=https://www.fifa.com/mensolympic/news/cote-d-ivoire-and-egypt-earn-tokyo-2020-berths|publisher=[[FIFA]]|date=19 November 2019|accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Team roster\n* Men's team event \u2013 1 team of 18 players\n\n==Rowing==\n{{main article|Rowing at the 2020 Summer Olympics|Rowing at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification}}\nIvory Coast qualified one boat in the men's single sculls for the Games by finishing sixth in the A-final and securing the fourth of five berths available at the 2019 FISA African Olympic Qualification Regatta in [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]], marking the country's debut in the sport.<ref>{{cite news|title=Africa goes for Tokyo 2020 Olympic and Paralympic qualification|url=http://www.worldrowing.com/news/africa-goes-for-tokyo-2020-olympic-and-paralympic-qualification|publisher=[[International Rowing Federation]]|date=16 October 2019|accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=\"2\"|Heats\n!colspan=\"2\"|Repechage\n!colspan=\"2\"|Quarterfinals\n!colspan=\"2\"|Semifinals\n!colspan=\"2\"|Final\n|- style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n!Time\n!Rank\n|-align=center\n|align=left|&nbsp;\n|align=left|[[Rowing at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's single sculls|Men's single sculls]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n<small>Qualification Legend: '''FA'''=Final A (medal); '''FB'''=Final B (non-medal); '''FC'''=Final C (non-medal); '''FD'''=Final D (non-medal); '''FE'''=Final E (non-medal); '''FF'''=Final F (non-medal); '''SA/B'''=Semifinals A/B; '''SC/D'''=Semifinals C/D; '''SE/F'''=Semifinals E/F; '''QF'''=Quarterfinals; '''R'''=Repechage</small>\n\n==Taekwondo==\n{{main article|Taekwondo at the 2020 Summer Olympics|Taekwondo at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification}}\nIvory Coast entered four athletes into the taekwondo competition at the Games. Defending Olympic champion [[Cheick Sallah Ciss\u00e9]] (men's 80 kg) and Rio 2016 bronze medalist [[Ruth Gbagbi]] (women's 67 kg) qualified directly for their respective weight classes by finishing among the top five taekwondo practitioners at the end of the WT Olympic Rankings. Meanwhile, reigning African Games champion [[Seydou Gban\u00e9]] and twenty-year-old rookie Aminata Traor\u00e9 secured the remaining spots on the Ivorian taekwondo squad with a top two finish each in the men's (+80 kg) and women's heavyweight category (+67 kg), respectively at the 2020 African Qualification Tournament in [[Rabat]], [[Morocco]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Taekwondo: Seydou Fofana premier Malien qualifi\u00e9 aux JO 2020|trans-title=Taekwondo: Seydou Fofana becomes the first Malian to qualify for 2020 Olympics|language=fr|url=http://www.rfi.fr/fr/sports/20200223-taekwondo-seydou-fofana-premier-malien-qualifi%C3%A9-jo-2020|publisher=[[Radio France Internationale]]|date=23 February 2020|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Six countries earned Olympic taekwondo berth on the second day of the African Qualification Tournament for Tokyo 2020|url=http://www.worldtaekwondo.org/six-countries-earned-olympic-taekwondo-berth-on-the-second-day-of-the-african-qualification-tournament-for-tokyo-2020/|publisher=[[World Taekwondo]]|date=23 February 2020|accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Athlete\n!rowspan=2|Event\n!Round of 16\n!Quarterfinals\n!Semifinals\n!Repechage\n!colspan=2|Final / {{tooltip|BM|Bronze medal match}}\n|- style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Opposition<br/>Result\n!Opposition<br/>Result\n!Opposition<br/>Result\n!Opposition<br/>Result\n!Opposition<br/>Result\n!Rank\n|- align=center\n|align=left|[[Cheick Sallah Ciss\u00e9]]\n|align=left|[[Taekwondo at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 80 kg|Men's \u221280 kg]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- align=center\n|align=left|[[Seydou Gban\u00e9]]\n|align=left|[[Taekwondo at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's +80 kg|Men's +80 kg]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- align=center\n|align=left|[[Ruth Gbagbi]]\n|align=left|[[Taekwondo at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 67 kg|Women's \u221267 kg]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- align=center\n|align=left|[[Aminata Traor\u00e9 (taekwondo)|Aminata Traor\u00e9]]\n|align=left|[[Taekwondo at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's +67 kg|Women's +67 kg]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Nations at the 2020 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Country at games navbox|Ivory Coast|Olympics}}\n\n[[Category:Nations at the 2020 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Ivory Coast at the Summer Olympics by year|2020]]\n[[Category:2020 in Ivorian sport]]\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixLintererrors usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivory_Coast_at_the_2020_Summer_Olympics"}
{"title_page": "Bing (TV series)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Bing\n| image                    = bing_title.jpg\n| image_size               = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    =\n| based_on                 = ''[[Ted Dewan#Bing Bunny|Bing Bunny]]'' by [[Ted Dewan]]\n| developer                = Acamar Films\n| writer                   = \n| screenplay               = \n| starring                 = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = Elliot Kerley<br>Trystan Tomos Thurtle<br>[[Mark Rylance]]\n| narrated                 = \n| composer                 = Julian Nott\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 2\n| num_episodes             = 130\n| list_episodes            = List of Bing episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lucy Murphy]]\n* [[Philip Bergkvist]]\n* [[Howard Litton]]}}\n| producer                 = Mikael Shields\n| editor                   = \n| runtime                  = 7 minutes\n| company                  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Acamar Films]]\n* [[Brown Bag Films]]\n* Tandem Films\n*Digitales Studios\n}}\n| distributor              = {{plainlist|\n* [[CBeebies]]\n* [[StudioCanal]]\n}}\n| channel                  = [[CBeebies]]<br>[[Disney Junior]]\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| released                 = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|df=yes|2014|06|09}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = <!-- To be used only for remakes, spin-offs, and adaptations. -->\n| website                  = http://www.bingbunny.com/\n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = http://www.acamarfilms.com/\n| production_website_title = \n}}\n\n'''''Bing''''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[CGI animation|CGI-animated]] [[children's television series]] based on the books by [[Ted Dewan]]. It is broadcast on UK TV channels [[CBeebies]] and [[Disney Junior]]; the series follows a pre-school bunny named Bing as he experiences the world around him. It uses small everyday occurrences to demonstrate how he learns new ways to manage situations with the help of his carer, Flop (voiced by [[Mark Rylance]]) and friends. The programme's central phrase is \"It's a Bing thing!\" which Flop intones at the end of each episode when Bing has successfully conquered a troubling task or enjoyed a new childhood experience.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of Bing episodes}}\nThe 1st series of 78, eight minute episodes show the \"mishaps, mess, energy and wonder of being a relatively new human being\". The programme focuses on real-life situations experienced by many toddlers and their parents.<ref name=Wolfe>{{cite news|last1=Wolfe|first1=Jennifer|title=Acamar Partners with Brown Bag Films and Tandem Films on \u2018Bing Bunny\u2019|url=http://www.awn.com/news/acamar-partners-brown-bag-films-and-tandem-films-bing-bunny|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=Animation World Network (AWN)|date=6 February 2014}}</ref> At the end, Bing summarizes what he has learnt in the episode, with Flop intoning \"It's a Bing thing\".<ref name=Brown>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Maggie|title=Mark Rylance voices CBeebies cartoon Bing|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/may/27/mark-rylance-cbeebies-cartoon-bing|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=The Guardian|date=27 May 2014}}</ref> The second season began airing on Cbeebies on 31 October 2019.\n\n==Main characters==\n[[File:Bing_Bunny_-_All_main_characters.jpg|thumb|240px|left|An image of the characters featured in Bing.]]\n\n* Bing (voiced by [[Elliot Kerley]] in series 1 and [[Rafferty Railton]] in series 2) is the titular protagonist of the programme. He is a 3-year-old black anthropomorphic bunny. His favourite toy is Hoppity Voosh, a rabbit superhero. He wears a green shirt, red chequered dungarees and black and white shoes and he loves to hum, whistle, pretend and do untroubling childlike things. \n* Flop (voiced by [[Mark Rylance]], while [[David Threlfall]] provides the voice of Flop in the 2nd series)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fletcher|first1=Harry|title=Mark Rylance to star in new CBeebies show Bing|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a573525/mark-rylance-to-star-in-new-cbeebies-show-bing/|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=Digital Spy|date=27 May 2014}}</ref> is Bing's carer, guiding Bing through his toddler life, entertaining him and soothing him when he faces a problem. He is a short orange-skinned creature.<ref name=\"BBC Bing\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/bing|title=Life - it\u2019s a Bing Thing! Bing comes to CBeebies with voice talent from Mark Rylance|date=27 May 2014|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n* Sula (voiced by Eve Bentley) is a 4-year-old female brown anthropomorphic elephant and one of Bing's best friends.<ref name=\"BBC Bing\"/>\n* Amma (voiced by Akiya Henry), is Sula's guardian (possibly mother). Amma runs the [[Day care|creche]] and [[park caf\u00e9]] which the programme's [[child]] characters sometimes visit. She is a short blue-skinned elephant-like creature.\n* Pando (voiced by Shai Portnoy in series 1 and [[Noah Hicks]] in series 2) is a 3-year-old anthropomorphic [[panda]] who is also Bing's second best friend,<ref name=\"BBC Bing\"/> and lives next door to him. He shares his catchphrase, \"Hoppity-voosh! \" with Bing. He wears a white shirt that doesn't completely cover his belly, black trainers and underwear and he hums, whistles, pretends and does untroubling childlike things just like Bing.\n* Padget (voiced by [[Bryony Hannah]]) is Pando's guardian (possibly mother). She runs the corner shop near to where Bing lives. Padget can sometimes be spotted out jogging or else driving her yellow tuk-tuk. She is a short green-skinned creature.\n* Coco (voiced by Jocelyn Macnab in series 1 and 2) is a white anthropomorphic bunny who is Bing's cousin and Charlie's older sister.<ref name=\"BBC Bing\"/> Coco is the eldest of the child characters.\n* Charlie (voiced by Poppy Hendley), is a white anthropomorphic bunny who is Coco's 1-year-old baby brother and Bing's cousin who cannot talk. He puts everything in his mouth and the others say, \"Don't chew it, Charlie!\"\n\n==Production==\n\n''Bing'' was based on a [[series of books]] called [[Ted Dewan#Bing Bunny|\"Bing Bunny\"]] written and illustrated by [[Ted Dewan]].<ref name=\"Rylance\">{{cite news|title=Mark Rylance joins CBeebies show Bing|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/ariel/27588797|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=BBC - Ariel|date=27 May 2014}}</ref> Acamar Films acquired the rights to ''Bing Bunny''<ref>{{cite news|title=Acamar Films Develops Animated \u2018Bing Bunny\u2019 Series|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/acamar-films-develops-animated-bing-bunny-series/|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=Animation Magazine|date=8 November 2012}}</ref> and produced the program in conjunction with Brown Bag Films and Tandem Films.<ref name=\"BBC Bing\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/bing|title=Life - it\u2019s a Bing Thing! Bing comes to CBeebies with voice talent from Mark Rylance|date=27 May 2014|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"Rylance\" /> The series was developed for CBeebies though initial episodes were viewable at [[MIPTV]].<ref name=\"Wolfe\" />\n\nHarperCollins Children's Books signed a deal with Acamar and The Licensing Company to re-publish the stories to link with the TV programme.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bing Bunny Books Head to TV|url=http://www.licensemag.com/license-global/bing-bunny-books-head-tv|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=License|date=9 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrington|first1=Joshua|title=HC to publish Bing Bunny TV tie-ins|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/hc-publish-bing-bunny-tv-tie-ins|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=The Book Seller|date=8 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Maybury|first1=David|title=Bing Bunny is in Production #NewShow|url=http://www.brownbagfilms.com/labs/entry/meet-bing-bunny-newshow|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=Brown Bag Films|date=7 February 2014}}</ref> The books were re-issued in 2013\u201314.<ref name=Wolfe/>\n\nThe 70-minute DVDs are released by Studio Canal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Milligan|first1=Mercedes|title=StudioCanal Bringing Acamar\u2019s \u2018Bing\u2019 to DVD|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/home-entertainment/studiocanal-bringing-acamars-bing-to-dvd/|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=Animation Magazine|date=26 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=BOUNDS OUT ON DVD WITH STUDIOCANAL|url=http://showmetheanimation.com/off-the-press/acamar-films-bing-bounds-out-on-dvd-with-studiocanal|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=Show me the animation|date=26 March 2015}}</ref> The first DVD \"Swing... and other episodes\" was released on 31 March 2015 and features 10 episodes - Bye Bye, Swing, Blocks, Ducks, Smoothie, Frog, Car Park, Shadow, Musical Statues, and Voo Voo. A second DVD was released on 15 June 2015 and is titled \"Storytime... and other episodes\", featuring a further 10 episodes - Storytime, Growing, Atchoo, Hide & Seek, Bake, Train, Say Goodbye, Lost, Picnic, and Balloon.\n\n[[Fisher Price]] have developed a range of ''Bing'' toys, which were released in July 2015, including \"play sets, figurines, role play items, ride-ons, musical toys, wooden toys, and soft toys\".<ref name=Fisher>{{cite news|title=Fisher-Price to Develop \u2018Bing\u2019 Toys|url=http://www.licensemag.com/license-global/fisher-price-develop-bing-toys|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=LicenseMag|date=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nthe show was supposed to be launched on Nick Jr for spring of 2019 in the USA. but was dropped from the network after no word on it.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n| 2015\n| Annecy International Animated Film Festival\n| TV Series\n| For \"Bye Bye\"\n| Nominated<ref>{{cite web|title=TV films in competition|url=http://www.annecy.org/about/archives/2015/official-selection:ser|website=Annecy|accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| [[BAFTA]]\n| Pre-School Animation\n| For full series\n| Nominated<ref>{{cite news|title=Children's Pre-School Animation in 2014|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2014/childrens/pre-school-animation|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=BAFTA}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| Pulcinella Award\n| TV Series for PreSchool\n| For full series\n| Nominated<ref>{{cite news|title=Nominations|url=http://www.cartoonsbay.com/en/festival_nomination/|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=Cartoons Bay|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222094116/http://www.cartoonsbay.com/en/festival_nomination/|archivedate=22 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolfe|first1=Jennifer|title=Cartoons on the Bay Unveils 2015 Pulcinella Award Nominees|url=http://www.awn.com/news/cartoons-bay-unveils-2015-pulcinella-award-nominees|accessdate=14 December 2015|publisher=Animation World Network|date=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| Writers Guild Award\n| Best Children's TV Episode\n| For \"Bye Bye\" by Denise Cassar & the Bing Writing Team\n| Won\n|-\n| 2016\n| International Emmy Kids Award\n| Pre-School\n| For full series\n| Won\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150107042217/http://www.bbc.co.uk/cbeebies/shows/bing Bing on Cbeebies]\n*[http://www.bingbunny.com Bing Bunny]\n*{{IMDb title|tt3789822}}\n\n[[Category:2014 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:British television programmes based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about rabbits and hares]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Bing\n| image                    = bing_title.jpg\n| image_size               = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| genre                    =\n| based_on                 = ''[[Ted Dewan#Bing Bunny|Bing Bunny]]'' by [[Ted Dewan]]\n| developer                = Acamar Films\n| writer                   = \n| screenplay               = \n| starring                 = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = Elliot Kerley<br>Trystan Tomos Thurtle<br>[[Mark Rylance]]\n| narrated                 = \n| composer                 = Julian Nott\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 2\n| num_episodes             = 130\n| list_episodes            = List of Bing episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Lucy Murphy]]\n* [[Philip Bergkvist]]\n* [[Howard Litton]]}}\n| producer                 = Mikael Shields\n| editor                   = \n| runtime                  = 7 minutes\n| company                  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Acamar Films]]\n* [[Brown Bag Films]]\n* Tandem Films\n*Digitales Studios\n}}\n| distributor              = {{plainlist|\n* [[CBeebies]]\n* [[StudioCanal]]\n}}\n| channel                  = [[CBeebies]]<br>[[Disney Junior]]\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| released